Introduction to OOP

OOP is one of the most important programming concepts.

Essential for interviews and technical exams.

Defined as an approach built on principles.


From Procedural to Object-Oriented
Procedural languages like C handled input/output directly.
OOP emerged to solve real-world problems by modeling everything as objects.
Objects combine data (attributes) and methods (functions).

Real-World Example: Zomato
Customer, order, restaurant, and delivery agent are all objects.
Customer data: name, phone, address.
Customer behavior: add to cart, make payment, track order.
Restaurant data: name, rating, address; behavior: update menu.

Advantages of OOP
Easier to maintain.
Reusable and scalable.
Secure and well-organized.
Models real-world problems effectively.
 
 Four Pillars of OOP
Encapsulation: Bind data and methods, restrict direct access.
Inheritance: Reuse properties from parent classes (e.g., premium customer inherits base customer attributes).
Polymorphism: Same method name used differently (e.g., “track order” by customer, restaurant, delivery agent).
Abstraction: Hide internal complexity (e.g., customer doesn’t see how food is prepared, only the final delivery).
 

Conclusion
OOP revolves around these four pillars.
Future lectures will dive deeper into each concept with execution examples.